{"title_page": "Beryl Measor", "text_new": "'''Beryl Measor''', (22 April 1908 \u2013 8 February 1965) was an English actress. She was born in [[Shanghai]],<ref name=bfi/> and studied at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London.<ref>\"Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\", ''The Times'', 31 July 1930, p. 12</ref> She was a star pupil, winning the RADA Silver Medal in 1931.<ref>\"Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\", ''The Times'', 8 August 1931,  p. 8</ref>\n\nAmong her stage roles was Madame Arcati in the original production of [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'', succeeding [[Margaret Rutherford]] in the part, during the record-breaking run.<ref>\"Theatres\", ''The Times'',  29 June 1942, p. 6</ref> She originated two roles in other plays by Coward: Edie in ''[[This Happy Breed]]'' and the central character's wise and long-suffering secretary, Monica Reed, in ''[[Present Laughter]]'', both in 1942.<ref>Coward, unnumbered introductory page</ref> In 1957 she was nominated for a [[Tony Awards|Tony award]] as Featured Actress in a Play for her performance as Miss Cooper in [[Terence Rattigan]]'s ''[[Separate Tables]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].<ref>[http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search \"Beryl Measor search\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831204617/http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search |date=2016-08-31 }}, Tony Awards, retrieved 19 March 2014</ref>\n\nMeasor was married to the actor [[Terence De Marney]]. She died in London at the age of 56.<ref name=bfi/>\n\n==Film and television roles==\n*''[[Almost a Honeymoon (1938 film)|Almost a Honeymoon]]''\u2013 Mabel, the barmaid (1938)\n*''Richard of Bordeaux''\u2013 Countess of Derby (1938)\n*''[[English Without Tears]]''\u2013 Miss Faljambe (1944)\n*''[[Dual Alibi]]''\u2013 Gwen (1947)\n*''[[Odd Man Out]]'' \u2013 Maudie (1947)\n*''[[The Mark of Cain (1947 film)|The Mark of Cain]]'' \u2013 Nurse Brand (1947)\n*''[[While the Sun Shines]]''\u2013 Woman in train (1947)\n*''Blithe Spirit '' Madame Arcati (1948)\n*''[[Esther Waters (film)|Esther Waters]]'' \u2013 Mrs Spires (1948)\n*''Morning Star'' \u2013 Amarilla Arbuthnot (1956)\n*''Please Murder Me'' \u2013 cast member (1958)\n*''Uncle Harry''\u2013 Hester Quincey (1958)\n*''How Did He Get It?''\u2013 Mrs Proudie (1959)\n*''No Wreath for the General Episode 3'' \u2013 middle-aged woman (1960)\n::Source: British Film Institute.<ref name=bfi>[http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6a9421fd \"Beryl Measor\"], British Film Institute, retrieved 19 March 2014</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{cite book| last= Coward| first= No\u00ebl| year= 1994| title= Plays, Four| location= London| publisher= Methuen| isbn= 0413461203| url-access= registration| url= https://archive.org/details/collectedplays00cowa}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Measor, Beryl}}\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n\n\n{{UK-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Beryl Measor''', (22 April 1908 \u2013 8 February 1965) was an English actress. She was born in [[Shanghai]],<ref name=bfi/> and studied at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London.<ref>\"Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\", ''The Times'', 31 July 1930, p. 12</ref> She was a star pupil, winning the RADA Silver Medal in 1931.<ref>\"Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\", ''The Times'', 8 August 1931,  p. 8</ref>\n\nAmong her stage roles was Madame Arcati in the original production of [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'', succeeding [[Margaret Rutherford]] in the part, during the record-breaking run.<ref>\"Theatres\", ''The Times'',  29 June 1942, p. 6</ref> She originated two roles in other plays by Coward: Edie in ''[[This Happy Breed]]'' and the central character's wise and long-suffering secretary, Monica Reed, in ''[[Present Laughter]]'', both in 1942.<ref>Coward, unnumbered introductory page</ref> In 1957 she was nominated for a [[Tony Awards|Tony award]] as Featured Actress in a Play for her performance as Miss Cooper in [[Terence Rattigan]]'s ''[[Separate Tables]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].<ref>[http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search \"Beryl Measor search\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831204617/http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search |date=2016-08-31 }}, Tony Awards, retrieved 19 March 2014</ref>\n\nMeasor was married to the actor [[Terence De Marney]]. She died in London at the age of 56.<ref name=bfi/>\n\n==Film and television roles==\n*''[[Almost a Honeymoon (1938 film)|Almost a Honeymoon]]''\u2013 Mabel, the barmaid (1938)\n*''Richard of Bordeaux''\u2013 Countess of Derby (1938)\n*''[[English Without Tears]]''\u2013 Miss Faljambe (1944)\n*''[[Dual Alibi]]''\u2013 Gwen (1947)\n*''[[Odd Man Out]]'' \u2013 Maudie (1947)\n*''[[The Mark of Cain (1947 film)|The Mark of Cain]]'' \u2013 Nurse Brand (1947)\n*''[[While the Sun Shines]]''\u2013 Woman in train (1947)\n*''Blithe Spirit '' Madame Arcati (1948)\n*''[[Esther Waters (film)|Esther Waters]]'' \u2013 Mrs Spires (1948)\n*''Morning Star'' \u2013 Amarilla Arbuthnot (1956)\n*''Please Murder Me'' \u2013 cast member (1958)\n*''Uncle Harry''\u2013 Hester Quincey (1958)\n*''How Did He Get It?''\u2013 Mrs Proudie (1959)\n*''No Wreath for the General Episode 3'' \u2013 middle-aged woman (1960)\n::Source: British Film Institute.<ref name=bfi>[http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6a9421fd \"Beryl Measor\"], British Film Institute, retrieved 19 March 2014</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{cite book| last= Coward| first= No\u00ebl| year= 1994| title= Plays, Four| location= London| publisher= Methuen| isbn= 0413461203| url-access= registration| url= https://archive.org/details/collectedplays00cowa}}\n\n\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Measor, Beryl}}\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n\n\n{{UK-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, added Empty section (1) tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beryl_Measor"}
{"title_page": "7flix", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox television channel\n| name              = 7flix\n| logofile          = 7flix_logo_without_background.png\n| logosize          = \n| logocaption       = \n| launch            = 28 February 2016\n| closed date       = \n| network           = [[Seven Network]]\n| owner             = [[Seven West Media]]\n| picture format    = [[576i]] ([[SDTV]]) [[16:9]]\n| share             = 2.2% nationally\n| share as of       = 2018 ratings year\n| share source      = <ref>https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/12/2018-ratings-multichannel-top-20.html</ref>\n| slogan            = ''We've Got the Fix''\n| country           = [[Australia]]\n| language          = English\n| broadcast area    = [[ATN|Sydney]], [[HSV (TV station)|Melbourne]], [[BTQ|Brisbane]], [[SAS (TV station)|Adelaide]], [[TVW|Perth]], [[Hobart]], [[STQ|Regional QLD]], [[NEN (TV station)|Northern NSW/Gold Coast]], [[CBN (Australian TV station)|Southern NSW/ACT]], [[AMV (TV station)|Regional Victoria]], [[PTV (TV station)|Mildura]]\n| former names      = \n| replaced names    = \n| replaced by names = \n| sister names      = [[Seven Network|Channel 7]]<br />[[7HD]]<br />[[7TWO]]<br />[[7mate]]<br />[[Openshop (TV channel)|Openshop]]<br />[[Racing.com]]\n| website           = [https://7plus.com.au/ 7plus.com.au/]\n| terr serv 1       = Freeview Seven owned ([[virtual channel|virtual]])\n| terr chan 1       = 76/66\n| terr serv 2       = Freeview Prime7 ([[virtual channel|virtual]])\n| terr chan 2       = 66\n| cable serv 1      = [[Foxtel]] ([[virtual channel|virtual]])\n| cable chan 1      = 187\n| online serv 1     = \n| online chan 1     = [https://7plus.com.au/live-tv?channel-id=7Flix 7plus]\n}}\n\n'''7flix''' is an Australian [[free-to-air]] digital television multichannel, which was launched by the [[Seven Network]] on 28 February 2016.<ref name=\"AdNewsLaunch\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jtVUSHagtOs|title=7Flix launch, watermark, PRG, promos|first=|last=Australian TV Fan|date=27 February 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 18 December 2015, a test pattern began broadcasting on channel 76 reading \"New Channel Coming Soon\".<ref name=\"testpattern\">{{cite web |url=http://eftm.com.au/2015/12/channel-7-launching-new-channel-could-hd-be-coming-24329 |title=Channel 7 launching new channel \u2013 Could HD be coming? |first=Trevor |last=Long |date=18 December 2015 |accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref> Seven acknowledged the broadcast and director of programming Angus Ross formally announced on 1 February 2016 that Seven was launching a new channel and more details would be released soon.<ref name=\"TVTtease\">{{cite web|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/programmers-wrap-2016-seven.html |title=Programmer\u2019s Wrap 2016: Seven |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref> During the ad-break of miniseries ''[[Molly (miniseries)|Molly]]'' on 7 February 2016, Seven announced that channel 76 would be named ''7flix'' and would be launched on 28 February 2016.<ref name=\"AdNewsLaunch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adnews.com.au/news/seven-launches-new-channel-7flix|title=Seven launches new channel - 7flix|first=Pippa|last=Chambers|work=AdNews|date=8 February 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|archivedate=8 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208013402/http://www.adnews.com.au/news/seven-launches-new-channel-7flix}}</ref><ref name=\"DeciderLaunch\">{{cite web |url=http://decidertv.com/page/2016/2/8/video-seven-releases-first-details-for-new-multi-channel-7flix |title=Video: Seven releases first details for new multi-channel 7Flix |last=Perry |first=Kevin |date=8 February 2016 |publisher=DeciderTV |access-date=8 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"mUmBRELLALaunch\">{{cite web |url=http://mumbrella.com.au/7flix-channel-76-seven-new-channel-344755 |title=Seven reveals new channel \u2013 7flix |last=Burrowes |first=Tim |date=7 February 2016 |publisher=mUmBRELLA |access-date=7 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TVTlaunch\">{{cite web|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/7flix-to-launch-feb-28.html |title=7flix to launch Feb 28 |date=8 February 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016}}</ref> The \"New Channel\" test pattern was then replaced with a continuous promo loop for 7flix.\n\n7flix began broadcasting at 6am on 28 February 2016 in MPEG-4,<ref name=\"ontheair\">{{cite web|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/7flix-is-on-the-air.html |title=7flix is on the air |date=28 February 2016 |accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref> as seen in a YouTube video showing the promo loop ending and a re-run of [[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon A Time]] starting afterwards.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The channel airs movies in its prime time slots with television series and other entertainment at other times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://decidertv.com/page/2016/2/27/complete-guide-to-week-one-of-7flix-channel7 |title=7Flix launches Tomorrow - Here's your Week One Guide|last=Perry |first=Kevin |date=28 February 2016 |publisher=DeciderTV |access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref> 7flix was added to Seven's live streaming service [[PLUS7|PLUS7 Live]] upon its launch.\n\nOn 13 April 2016, it was announced the channel would amend its schedule, shifting its focus from movies to more American dramas. This change began in the weeks prior when ''Grey's Anatomy'' premiered at 8:30pm, which was initially designated as a \"movie-exclusive\" timeslot. The change also sees the addition of repeats of [[Criminal Minds]] to Thursday nights.<ref name=\"Drama\">{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|title=Less movies, more drama on 7flix.|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2016/04/less-movies-more-drama-on-7flix.html|work=TV Tonight|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2016, 7flix became available on more TVs as the channel switched to MPEG-2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/7flixAU/videos/1111410588920622/|title=7Flix|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 2017, 18 months after launching in metropolitan areas, [[Prime7]] announced that it would carry 7flix to its regional stations in [[NEN (TV station)|northern]] and [[CBN (Australian TV station)|southern New South Wales]], [[AMV (TV station)|regional Victoria]] and [[PTV (TV station)|Mildura]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mumbrella.com.au/prime7-launches-7flix-across-regional-nsw-act-victoria-gold-coast-462563 |title=NEWSPrime7 launches 7Flix across regional NSW, ACT, Victoria and Gold Coast |last=Samios |first=Zoe |date=3 August 2017 |website=Mumbrella |access-date= 4 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"PrimeTVTonight\"/> The channel was launched at 6:00 am of 3 September on digital channel 66, in an MPEG-4 format.<ref name=\"Prime7flix\">{{cite web |url=https://au.prime7.yahoo.com/a1/7flix |title=7flix \u2014 Prime7 |date=3 August 2017 |publisher=Prime Media Group |access-date=4 August 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019 it was announced that 7flix will rebrand in 2020 to target a young female audience. It will also air content from the defunct [[7food network]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/12/seven-confirms-7food-channel-closure.html|title=Seven confirms 7food channel closure|date=2019-12-16|website=TV Tonight|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n{{original research|section|date=April 2017|discuss=Talk:7flix#Encores vs repeats}}\n{{Cleanup list|section|date=April 2017}}\nThe launch titles for 7flix included new episodes of US series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon A Time]]'', ''[[The Muppets (TV series)|The Muppets]]'', ''[[The Mindy Project]]'', ''[[Cougar Town]]'' and ''[[The Amazing Race]]'', which had previously debuted on the [[Seven Network]].<ref name=\"7flixschedulelaunch\">{{cite web|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/returning-once-upon-a-time-the-amazing-race-the-muppets-mindy-project.html/|title=Returning: Once Upon a Time, The Amazing Race, The Muppets|date=22 February 2016|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref> Premiere series such as ''[[Black-ish]]'', ''[[Grandfathered (TV series)|Grandfathered]]'', ''[[Galavant]]'' and ''[[Agent Carter (TV series)|Agent Carter]]'' debuted at a later date.<ref name=\"7flixschedulelaunch\"/><ref name=\"galavant\">{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|title=Airdate: Galavant|work=TV Tonight|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2016/03/airdate-galavant.html|date=9 March 2016|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> Throughout 2016, new episodes of ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'', ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]'', ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]'' and ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]'' aired exclusively on the channel.<ref name=\"OctoberUpdate\">{{cite web|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2016/10/gone-how-to-get-away-with-murder-bumped-quantico.html|title=Gone: How to Get Away with Murder. Bumped: Quantico |date=21 October 2016|accessdate=27 October 2016|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref><ref name=\"multichannelsurvey2016\">{{cite web|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2016/06/multichannel-survey-2016-7two-7mate-7flix.html |title= Multichannel Survey 2016: 7TWO / 7mate / 7flix|date=21 June 2016|accessdate=1 May 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=TV Tonight}}</ref> Also featured on the channel were marathons of ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'',<ref name=\"BigBang\">{{cite web|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2016/10/big-bang-marathon-is-a-big-deal-for-7flix.html|title=''Big Bang'' marathon is a big deal for 7flix |date=20 October 2016|accessdate=27 October 2016|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref> but this series was now returns on [[Nine Network|Nine]].\n\n7flix initially aired a variety of children's series from [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group|Disney]] including ''[[Austin & Ally]]'', ''[[Dog with a Blog]]'', ''[[I Didn't Do It (TV series)|I Didn't Do It]]'', ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'', ''[[Kirby Buckets]]'', ''[[Lab Rats (U.S. TV series)|Lab Rats]]'' and ''[[Mighty Med]]''.<ref name=\"SDEnd2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/10/home-shopping-replaces-saturday-disney.html|title=Home Shopping replaces Saturday Disney|date=1 October 2016|accessdate=6 March 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref> The daytime schedule for the channel consists of classic sitcoms such as ''[[Benson (TV series)|Benson]]'', ''[[Bewitched]]'', ''[[Good Times]]'', ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'' and ''[[Who's The Boss?]]''<ref name=\"ontheair\"/> 7flix also airs encores of local programmes from the Seven Network, including ''[[House Rules (Australian TV series)|House Rules]]'' and ''[[First Dates (Australia)|First Dates]]''.<ref name=\"14May2017\">{{cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/7flix-program-schedule-week-commencing-may-14-2017-4426159|title=7flix Program Schedule for Week Commencing May 14, 2017|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017|first=|last=|work=[[Mumbrella]]|publisher=Focal Attractions Pty Ltd}}</ref><ref name=\"ontheair\"/>\n\nIn 2017, US drama ''[[The Astronaut Wives Club]]'' debuted, along with the premieres of comedy series ''[[Marry Me (U.S. TV series)|Marry Me]]'', ''[[Bad Teacher (TV series)|Bad Teacher]]'', ''[[Dr. Ken]]'' and ''[[The Real O'Neals]]''.<ref name=\"Astronaut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2017/02/airdate-astronaut-wives-club-returning-scandal.html|title=Airdate: Astronaut Wives Club. Returning: Scandal |date=21 February 2017|accessdate=29 May 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MarryMe\">{{cite web|url=http://tvtonight.com.au/2017/06/airdate-marry-me-update-quantico.html|title=Airdate: Marry Me. Update: Quantico|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref><ref name=\"BadTeacher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2017/08/airdate-bad-teacher.html |title=Airdate: ''Bad Teacher'' |date=10 August 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref><ref name=\"DrKen\">{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2017/11/airdate-dr-ken-the-real-oneals.html |title=Airdate: ''Dr. Ken'', ''The Real O\u2019Neals''.|date=21 November 2017|accessdate=21 November 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref> Australian comedy short form series ''Bent 101'' also made its debut on the channel.<ref name=\"Bent101\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2017/05/airdate-bent-101.html|title=Airdate: Bent 101 |date=26 May 2017|accessdate=14 June 2017|first=David|last=Knox|work=[[TV Tonight]]}}</ref>\n\n''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'' was added to 7flix in 2018, returning to the Seven Network as part of a deal with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]].<ref name=\"himym\"/>\n\n===Current programming===\n====Adult animation====\n* ''[[The Simpsons]]'' (repeats; shared with 7mate)\n* ''[[Futurama]]'' (repeats; shared with 7mate)\n\n====Children's====\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[Beat Bugs]]''\n* ''[[The Deep (2015 TV series)|The Deep]]''\n* ''[[Flushed (game show)|Flushed]]''\n* ''[[In Your Dreams (TV series)|In Your Dreams]]''\n* ''[[It's Academic (Australian game show)|It's Academic]]''\n* ''[[Match It]]''\n* ''News of the Wild''\n* ''[[Sally Bollywood: Super Detective]]''\n* ''[[Spit It Out (TV series)|Spit it Out]]''\n{{colend}}\n\n====Comedy====\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]''\n* ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]''\n* ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]''<ref name=\"himym\">{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/01/simpsons-set-for-7mate-mash-to-7two.html |title= Simpsons set for 7mate, MASH to 7TWO.|date=30 January 2018|accessdate=1 February 2018|first=David|last=Knox|work=T