itish Columbia]]\n|4\n| Long gun\n| No\n|Four people killed in three different locations by a man reported to have used a rifle, and who immediately turned himself in to police.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/penticton-shootings-live-updates-and-what-we-know-so-far |title = Penticton shootings: Live updates and what we know so far &#124; Vancouver Sun|date = April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2019 Northern British Columbia murders]]\n|July 14-19, 2019\n|[[British Columbia]]\n|3\n| Long gun\n| Yes\n|An Australian and an American tourist were found dead. Five days later, another man was found dead.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.insider.com/british-columbia-murders-missing-teens-link-rcmp-2019-7 |title = 2 murders, a death, and 2 disappearances in a remote, wild part of Canada could all be connected, police say}}</ref> On July 23, the RCMP initiated a country-wide manhunt for the two outstanding suspects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/ten-days-four-provinces-how-two-b-c-suspected-fugitives-continue-to-evade-rcmp|title=Ten days, four provinces: How two B.C. fugitives continue to evade RCMP {{!}} National Post|last=News|last2=Canada|date=2019-07-29|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> On August 7, two bodies, later identified as the suspects, were found in dense brush near the [[Nelson River]] in [[Manitoba]]. Autopsies and press conference reported death by suicide.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/rcmp-significant-announcement-1.5239053|title=Bodies found in northern Manitoba believed to be 2 B.C. fugitives: RCMP|last=Glowacki |first=Laura|date=August 7, 2019|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2019 Markham home massacre]]\n|July 28, 2019\n|[[Markham, Ontario]]\n| 4\n| Knife\n| No\n|23-year-old Menhaz Zaman is charged after allegedly killing four family members by cutting their throats in a Markham home.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/07/28/four-bodies-found-in-markham-ont-home-one-man-in-custody/ | title=Four bodies found in Markham, Ont., home; one man in custody}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nova Scotia killings]]\n|April 18-19, 2020\n|Multiple locations in [[Nova Scotia]]\n| At least 18 (including the gunman)\n| Unknown firearms\n| Unknown\n|51-year-old Gabriel Wortman, shot and killed at least 17 people, including a Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) officer Heidi Stevenson, and later died himself.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html</ref><ref>https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/newsalert-const-heidi-stevenson-identified-as-rcmp-officer-killed-in-shooting/amp</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of conflicts in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}{{massacres}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M}}\n[[Category:Lists of massacres by country|Canada]]\n[[Category:Canada history-related lists|massacres]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}} \n{{more citations needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nThis is a list of events in [[Canada]] for which one of the commonly accepted names includes the word '''''[[massacres]]'''''. ''Massacre'' is defined in the ''Oxford English Dictionary'' as \"the indiscriminate and brutal slaughter of people or (less commonly) animals; carnage, butchery, slaughter in numbers\". It also states that the term is used \"in the names of certain massacres of history\". Thomas W. Gallant definition of ''Massacres''; deliberate slaughter of a large number of people in a violent way, especially when they cannot defend themselves.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gallant|first1=Thomas W.|authorlink=Thomas Gallant (historian)|title=review of Levene, Roberts The Massacre in History|journal=Crime, History & Societies|date=2001|volume= 5|issue= 1}}</ref><ref Name=DictionaryDefinition>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mastsacre?s=t \"massacre.\" Dictionary.com Unabridged. Random House, Inc. December 23, 2014.]</ref>  The following is a list of [[massacre]]s that have occurred in [[Canada]] and its predecessors. Some events in which numerous individuals were [[wound]]ed are also included.\n\n:*For '''single perpetrator events and shooting sprees''', see [[List of rampage killers|Lists of rampage killers]] and [[:Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n:*For '''school shootings''', see [[:Category:School shootings in Canada]]/[[:Category:School killings in Canada]]\n:*For '''North American First Nations massacres''', see [[List of Indian massacres|List of American First Nations massacres]].\n:*For '''terrorism''', see [[Terrorism in Canada]].\n:*For '''serial killers''', see [[List of serial killers by country#Canada|List of serial killers in Canada]].\n==List==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"\"width:120px;\"\"|Name\n! style=\"\"width:65px;\"\" data-sort-type=\"\"date\"\" |Date\n! style=\"\"width:120px;\"\"|Location\n! style=\"\"width:25px;\"\"|Dead / Injured / Captives\n! style=\"\"width:25px;\"\"|Mechanism of injury\n! style=\"\"width:25px;\"\"|Perpetrator suicide\n!class=\"\"unsortable\"\"|Notes\n|-\n|[[Lachine massacre]]\n|August 5, 1689\n|[[Lachine, Quebec]]\n| est. 24 to 250\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n| Total population of Lachine estimated at 375.  Part of [[King George's War]]\n|-\n|[[Battle at Port-la-Joye|Port-la-Joye Massacre]]\n|July 11, 1746\n|Port-la-Joye, \u00cele Saint-Jean.  The location now known as [[Hillsborough River (Prince Edward Island)]].\n|34 / 0\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n| Acadian and Mi'kmaqs killed 34 unarmed British (27 soldiers and 7 sailors).  Part of [[King George's War]]\n|-\n|[[Battle of Grand Pr\u00e9|Grand-Pr\u00e9 Massacre]]\n|February 10, 1747\n|[[Grand-Pr\u00e9, Nova Scotia]]\n|67 / 0 / 40\n|Military and allies\n|na\n| Acadian and Mi'kmaqs took est. 40 prisoners after attack.  Part of [[King George's War]]\n|-\n|[[Raid on Dartmouth|Dartmouth Massacre]]\n|May 13, 1751\n|[[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia]]\n|bet. 7 and 20 / 0 / bet. 6 and 14 \n|First Nations violence\n|na\n| One of seven raids by Mi'kmaqs on British and New England forces, usually very violence with deaths and scalpings.  Part of [[Father Le Loutre's War]]\n|-\n|[[St. Francis Raid|St. Francis Massacre]]\n|October 4, 1759\n|[[Odanak]], [[Quebec]]\n|30\u2013200 / unk / bet. 7 and 20\n|Military and allies\n|na\n| Raid by [[Robert Rogers (British Army officer)|Robert Rogers]]' Rangers, which was pursued and depleted before crossing back into New England.  Part of [[French and Indian War]]\n|-\n|[[Bloody Falls Massacre]]\n|July 17, 1771\n|The location now known as [[Kugluk/Bloody Falls Territorial Park]] near [[Kugluktuk, Nunavut]]\n|20\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n|Alleged massacre between indigenous peoples\n|-\n|[[Chilcotin War]]\n|April 30, 1864\n|[[Bute Inlet]], [[British Columbia]]\n|19\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n|Massacre of road workers in a series of attacks by indigenous peoples\n|-\n|[[Cypress Hills massacre]]\n|June 1, 1873\n|[[Cypress Hills (Canada)|Cypress Hills]], [[Saskatchewan]]\n|23\n|Civilian violence\n|na\n| Mass murder perpetrated by American bison and wolf hunters, and American and Canadian whisky traders and cargo haulers, against a camp of Assiniboine people. One of the main contributing reasons for the formation of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]].\n|-\n|[[Black Donnellys]] massacre\n|February 4, 1880\n|[[Lucan Biddulph]], [[Ontario]]\n|5\n|Civilian violence\n|na\n| Murder of five members of the Donnelly family by an armed mob, after which their farm was burned down. The event was the culmination of long-standing conflict between the family and other residents, none of the mob were ever convicted.\n|-\n|[[Frog Lake Massacre]]\n|April 2, 1885\n|[[Frog Lake, Alberta]]\n|9\n|Military\n|na\n|p