{"title_page": "Ministry of Education and Research (Norway)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = Royal Ministry of Education and Research\n|nativename      = Det kongelige kunnskapsdepartement\n|nativename_a    =\n|nativename_r    =\n|logo            = Statslogo.svg\n|logo_width      = 80px\n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|formed          = {{Start date and age|1814|df=yes}}\n|preceding1      =\n|preceding2      =\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    = [[Government of Norway]]\n|headquarters    = [[Oslo]]\n|employees       =\n|budget          =\n|minister1_name  = [[Guri Melby]]\n|minister1_pfo   =Minister of Education and Integration\n|minister2_name  = [[Henrik Asheim]]\n|minister2_pfo   = Minister of Research and Higher Education\n|chief1_name     =\n|chief1_position =\n|chief2_name     =\n|chief2_position =\n|parent_agency   =\n|child1_agency   =\n|child2_agency   =\n|website         = [http://www.regjeringen.no/kd regjeringen.no/kd]\n|footnotes       =\n}}\nThe '''Royal Ministry of Education and Research''' ({{lang-no|Det kongelige kunnskapsdepartement}}, lit. \"Royal Department of Knowledge\"; short name ''Kunnskapsdepartementet'') is a [[Politics of Norway|Norwegian government]] ministry responsible for [[education in Norway|education]], research and [[kindergarten]]s. The ministry was established in 1814 as the Royal Ministry of Church and Education Affairs.\n\nThe current Minister of Education and Integration is [[Guri Melby]] of the [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]] and the current Minister of Research and Higher Education is [[Henrik Asheim]] of the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]].\n\nThe department reports to the legislature ([[Storting]]et). Traditionally this ministry was also responsible for church affairs, but this function was transferred to the [[Norwegian Ministry of Culture and Church Affairs|Ministry of Culture and Church Affairs]] in 2002.\n\n==History==\n\nThe ministry was established in 1814, following the dissolution of the united kingdom of [[Denmark\u2013Norway]], in which the joint central government administration of the two formally separate but closely integrated kingdoms had been based in [[Copenhagen]]. Originally named the Ministry of Church and Education Affairs, the ministry was the first of six government ministries established in 1814, and was also known as the First Ministry. The other ministries were the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Police, the Ministry of the Interior, the Ministry of Finance and the Ministry of War. Although Norway was in a loose [[Union between Sweden and Norway|personal union with Sweden]] with a common foreign and defence policy until 1905, church and education policy was entirely the domain of the respective national governments.\n\n==Organisations==\n===Political staff<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/kd/about-the-ministry/other-political-staff.html?id=608 Ministry of Education and Research \u2013 Political staff]</ref>===\n* [[Torbj\u00f8rn R\u00f8e Isaksen]], minister of Education and Research ([[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]])\n* State Secretaries, [[Bj\u00f8rn Haugstad]] and [[Birgitte Jordahl]]\n* Political Adviser, [[Magnus Thue]]\n\n===Departments===\n* Department of Administration and Development\n* Department of Early Childhood Education and Care<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/kd/About-the-Ministry/Organisation.html?id=610 |title=Organisation |accessdate=June 27, 2007 |author=Norwegian Ministry of Education and Research}}</ref>\n* Department of Education and Training\n* Department of Governance and Finance\n* Department of Higher Education\n* Department of Policy Analysis, Lifelong Learning and International Affairs\n* Department of Research\n* The Communication Unit\n\n===Subsidiaries===\nThe following [[etat|government agencies]] are subordinate to the ministry:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/nb/dep/kd/dep/Underliggende-etater.html?id=115208 |title=Underliggende etater |accessdate=June 27, 2007 |author=Norwegian Ministry of Education and Research |language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n* [[Research Council of Norway]] ''Norges forskningsr\u00e5d'' ([http://www.forskningsradet.no/en/Home_page/1177315753906 Official site]) In charge of research funding and research policy.\n* [[Norwegian Directorate for Education and Training]], or ''Utdanningsdirektoratetet'' ([http://www.udir.no Official site]) Responsible for the development of primary and secondary education. Approves the primary and secondary school curriculum.\n* [[Centre for ICT in education]]\n* [[Foreldreutvalget for grunnskolen]] ([http://www.fug.no/forside.138180.en.html Official site]) Cooperation between parents and school authorities.\n* [[Norway Opening Universities]], or ''Norgesuniversitetet'' ([http://norgesuniversitetet.no/about Official site]) Think tank for lifelong learning and e-learning in higher education and provides funding to distance learning initiantives.\n* [[Norwegian Agency for Quality Assurance in Education]], or ''Nasjonalt organ for kvalitet i utdanningen'' ([http://www.nokut.no/en/ Official site]) Quality assurance for colleges and secondary vocational training, as well as approving degrees from foreign countries.\n* [[Norwegian Centre for International Cooperation in Higher Education]], or ''Senter for internasjonalisering av h\u00f8yere utdanning'' ([http://www.siu.no Official site]) Promotes international cooperation in higher education and research.\n* [[Norwegian Institute for Adult Learning]], or ''VOX-l\u00e6ring for arbeidslivet'' ([https://archive.today/20130222214637/http://www.vox.no/templates/CommonPage.aspx?id=3239 Official site]) Promotes adult learning within reading, writing, arithmetic and ICT.\n* [[Norwegian Institute of International Affairs]], or ''Norsk utenrikspolitisk institutt'' ([http://www.nupi.no Official site]) Foreign policy research.\n* [[Norwegian Meteorological Institute]], or ''Meteorologisk institutt'' ([http://www.met.no Official site]) Performs weather observations and forecasts.\n* [[Norwegian Social Research]], or ''Norsk institutt for forskning om oppvekst, velferd og aldring'' ([http://www.nova.no Official site]) Research.\n* [[Norwegian State Educational Loan Fund]], or ''Statens l\u00e5nekasse for utdanning'' ([http://www.lanekasen.no Official site]) Grands loans and scholarships to students.\n* [[Norwegian Universities and Colleges Admission Service]], or ''Samordna opptak'' ([http://www.samordnaopptak.no Official site]) Coordinates admission to most undergraduate courses at state universities and colleges.\n* [[Vea: Statens fagskole for gartnere og blomsterdekorat\u00f8rer]] ([https://www.vea-fs.no/ Official site]) Educates gardeners and flower decorators at secondary school level.\n\n===Universities===\n* [[Nord University]], or '' Nord universitet'' ([http://www.nord.no Official site])\n* [[Norwegian University of Life Sciences]], or ''Universitetet for milj\u00f8- og biovitenskap'' ([http://www.unb.no Official site])\n* [[Norwegian University of Science and Technology]], or ''Norges teknisk-naturvitenskapelige universitet'' ([http://www.ntnu.no Official site])\n* [[University of Bergen]], or ''Universitetet i Bergen'' ([http://www.uib.no Official site])\n* [[University of Oslo]], or ''Universitetet i Oslo'' ([http://www.uio.no Official site])\n* [[University of Stavanger]], or ''Universitetet i Stavanger'' ([http://www.uis.no Official site])\n* [[University of Troms\u00f8]], or ''Universitetet i Troms\u00f8'' ([http://www.uit.no Official site])\n* [[University of Agder]], or ''Universitetet i Agder'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20070811183825/http://www.hia.no/ Official site])\n\n===Specialised Colleges===\n* [[Oslo School of Architecture and Design]], or ''Arkitektur- og designh\u00f8gskolen i Oslo'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20190924114140/https://aho.no/ Official site])\n* [[Norwegian School of Economics and Business Administration]], or ''Norges handelsh\u00f8gskole'' ([http://www.nhh.no Official site])\n* [[Norwegian School of Sport Sciences]], or ''Norges idrettsh\u00f8gskole'' ([http://www.nih.no Official site])\n* [[Norwegian Academy of Music]], or ''Norges musikkh\u00f8gskole'' ([http://www.nmh.no Official site])\n* [[Norwegian School of Veterinary Science]], or ''Norges vetrin\u00e6rh\u00f8gskole'' ([http://www.veths.no Official site])\n\n===Regional University Colleges===\n* [[Bergen National Academy of the Arts]], or ''Kunsth\u00f8gskolen i Bergen'' ([http://www.khib.no Official site])\n* [[Harstad University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Harstad'' ([http://www.hih.no Official site])\n* [[Hedmark University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Hedmark'' ([http://www.hihm.no Official site])\n* [[Lillehammer University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Lillehammer'' ([http://www.hil.no Official site])\n* [[Molde University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Molde'' ([http://www.himolde.no Official site])\n* [[Oslo National Academy of the Arts]], or ''Kunsth\u00f8gskolen i Oslo'' ([http://www.khio.no Official site])\n* [[Oslo and Akershus University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Oslo og Akershus'' ([http://www.hioa.no Official site])\n* [[S\u00e1mi University College]], or ''Samisk h\u00f8gskole '' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20070903082308/http://www.samiskhs.no/ Official site])\n* [[University College of Southeast Norway]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i S\u00f8r\u00f8st Norge'' ([https://www.usn.no Official site])\n* [[Volda University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Volda'' ([http://www.hivolda.no Official site])\n* [[Western Norway University of Applied Sciences]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i Vestlandet'' ([http://www.hvl.no Official site])\n* [[\u00d8stfold University College]], or ''H\u00f8gskolen i \u00d8stfold'' ([http://www.hiof.no Official site])\n\n===Limited companies===\n* [[Norwegian Social Science Data Services]], or ''Norsk samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste'' ([http://www.nsd.uib.no Official site]) Information and data services for higher education and research.\n* [[Svalbard University Centre]], or ''Universitetssenteret p\u00e5 Svalbard'' ([http://www.unis.no Official site]) Research on Svalbard.\n* [[Uninett]] ([http://www.uninett.no Official site]) Operates the university/college/research internet communication network and the norid domain register.\n* [[Simula Research Laboratory]] ([http://www.simula.no Official site]) (80%, Research)\n\n==Ministers of Education==\n===Key===\n{{legend2|#E6E6AA|[[Christian Democratic Party of Norway|Christian Democratic Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n{{legend2|#AACCFF|[[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n{{legend2|#AACC99|[[Centre Party (Norway)|Agrarian / Centre Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n{{legend2|#FFB6B6|[[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n{{legend2|#F4AAC2|[[Socialist Left Party (Norway)|Socialist Left Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}} <br>\n{{legend2|#AEE8A8|[[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]] |border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n{{legend2|#ADD8E6|[[Free-minded Liberal Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n{{legend2|#C0C0C0|[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n==Ministers for the 1st Department (1814-1819)==\n\n==Ministers of Education and Church Affairs (1819-1884)==\n\n===Ministers of Education and Church Affairs (1884\u20131945)===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n! scope=col class=unsortable | Photo\n! scope=col | Name\n! scope=col | Party\n! scope=col | Took office\n! scope=col | Left office\n! scope=col | Tenure\n! scope=col | Cabinet\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Elias_Blix_OB.SZ01291.jpg|100x100px]]\n! scope=row | [[Elias Blix]]\n| style=\"background:#AEE8A8\" | [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal]] || 26 June 1884 || 15 August 1885 |