>\n|-\n| align=center |[[File:Norges finansminister Kristin Halvorsen vid Nordiska Radets session i Helsingfors 2008-10-28 (1).jpg|100x100px]]\n! scope=row | {{sortname|Kristin|Halvorsen}}\n| style=\"background:#F4AAC2\" | [[Socialist Left Party (Norway)|Socialist Left]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2009|10|20}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2013|10|16}} || {{age in years and days|2009|10|20|2013|10|16}} || [[Stoltenberg's Second Cabinet|Stoltenberg II]] || align=center | <ref name=stoltenberg2>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/modern-times/governments-since-1945/jens-stoltenbergs-second-government.html?id=449424 |publisher=[[Government.no]] |title=Jens Stoltenberg's Second Government |accessdate=23 March 2012 |archivedate=23 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66Nt0FwU5?url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/modern-times/governments-since-1945/jens-stoltenbergs-second-government.html?id=449424 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Torbj\u00f8rn R\u00f8e Isaksen Sentralbanksjefens \u00e5rstale 2018 (191730).jpg|75px]] \n! scope=row |{{sortname|Torbj\u00f8rn R\u00f8e|Isaksen}} \n| style=\"background:#AACCFF\" |[[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2013|10|16}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2018|1|17}}|| {{age in years and days|2013|10|16|2018|1|17}} ||[[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg]] || align=center | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/kld/id668/ |publisher=[[Government.no]] |title=Erna Solbergs's Government |accessdate=12 January 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center |  [[File:Jan Tore Sanner - 2010-05-08 at 10-34-24.jpg|75px]] \n! scope=row |{{sortname|Jan Tore|Sanner}} \n| style=\"background:#AACCFF\" |[[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2018|1|17}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|1|24}} || {{age in years and days|2018|1|17|2020|1|24}} ||[[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg]] || align=center |\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dn.no/politikk/regjeringen/norge/erna-solberg/dette-er-solbergs-nye-regjering/2-1-253734 |publisher=Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv |title=This Is Solberg's New Cabinet |date= 17 January 2018 | accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Trine Skei Grande (175428).jpg|75px]]\n! scope=row | {{sortname|Trine Skei|Grande}}\n| style=\"background:#AEE8A8\" | [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|1|24}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|3|13}}|| {{age in years and days|2020|1|24|2020|3|13}} || [[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg]] || align=center | <ref name=NRK>{{cite web | url=https://www.nrk.no/norge/slik-er-solberg-regjeringen-4.0-1.14873946 | publisher= [[NRK]] | title= This Is Solberg's Cabinet 4.0 | date= 24 January 2020 | accessdate= 24 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center | [[File: Guri Melby, Venstre.jpg|75px]]\n! scope=row | {{sortname|Guri|Melby}}\n| style=\"background:#AEE8A8\" | [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|3|13}} || present || {{age in years and days|2020|3|13}} || [[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg]] || align=center | <ref name= [[NRK]]>{{cite web | url= https://www.nrk.no/nordland/guri-melby-_v_-ny-kunnskaps--og-integreringsminister-og-odd-emil-ingebrigtsen-ny-fiskeriminister-1.14942304 | language= Norwegian | title= Guri Melby (L) New Education Minister and Odd Emil Ingebrigtsen New Fisheries Minister | publisher= [[NRK]] | date= 13 March 2020 | accessdate = 13 March 2020}}</ref> \n|}\n\n==Minister of Higher Education==\nThe '''Minister of Higher Education''' is responsible for policies regarding higher education. The post was originally established in 2007, before its responsibilities were transferred to the Ministry of Culture. The post was re-established when the Liberal Party joined the Solberg Cabinet in 2018. \n\n===Key===\n{{legend2|#F4AAC2|[[Socialist Left Party (Norway)|Socialist Left Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}} <br>\n{{legend2|#AEE8A8|[[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}} <br>\n{{legend2|#AACCFF|[[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br>\n\n===Ministers===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n! scope=col class=unsortable | Photo\n! scope=col | Name\n! scope=col | Party\n! scope=col | Took office\n! scope=col | Left office\n! scope=col | Tenure\n! scope=col | Cabinet\n! scope=col class=unsortable | Ref\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Tora Aasland (1).jpg|100x100px]]\n! scope=row | {{sortname|Tora|Aasland}}\n| style=\"background:#F4AAC2\"|[[Socialist Left Party (Norway)|Socialist Left]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2007|10|18}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2012|3|23}}|| {{age in years and days|2007|10|18|2012|3|23}} ||[[Stoltenberg's Second Cabinet|Stotlenberg II]] || align=center | <ref name=stoltenberg2>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/modern-times/governments-since-1945/jens-stoltenbergs-second-government.html?id=449424 |publisher=[[Government.no]] |title=Jens Stoltenberg's Second Government |accessdate=23 March 2012 |archivedate=23 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66Nt0FwU5?url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/modern-times/governments-since-1945/jens-stoltenbergs-second-government.html?id=449424 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center | [[File:Iselin Nyb\u00f8 (V) (9047619417).jpg|100x100px]]\n! scope=row |{{sortname|Iselin|Nyb\u00f8}}\n| style=\"background:#AEE8A8\" |[[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2018|1|17}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|1|24}}|| {{age in years and days|2018|1|17|2020|1|24}} ||[[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg]] || align=center |<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.venstre.no/artikkel/2018/01/17/venstre-i-regjering/ |publisher=[[Liberal Party (Norway)|venstre.no]] |title=The Liberals In Government |date= 17 January 2018 | accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center | [[File:Henrik asheim cropped.jpg|100x100px]]\n! scope=row |{{sortname|Henrik|Asheim}}\n| style=\"background:#AACCFF\" |[[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|1|24}} || present || {{age in years and days|2020|1|24}} ||[[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg]] || align=center |<ref name=NRK>{{cite web | url=https://www.nrk.no/norge/slik-er-solberg-regjeringen-4.0-1.14873946 | publisher= [[NRK]] | title= This Is Solberg's Cabinet 4.0 | date= 24 January 2020 | accessdate= 24 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/kd.html?id=586}}\n\n{{Ministries of Norway}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norwegian Ministry Of Education And Research}}\n[[Category:Government ministries of Norway|Education and Research]]\n[[Category:Education in Norway]]\n[[Category:Education ministries|Norway]]\n[[Category:Science and technology ministries|Norway]]\n[[Category:Ministries established in 1814]]\n[[Category:1814 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Research ministries]]\n", "name_user": "MariusLeland19", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMinisters of Education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ministry_of_Education_and_Research_(Norway)"}
{"title_page": "Pilotbird", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Pilotbird\n| image = Pilotbird - Blue Mountains.jpg\n| image_caption = Pilotbird, Blue Mountains\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704513/0 |title=''Pycnoptilus floccosus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Pycnoptilus\n| parent_authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n| species = floccosus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n}}\n\nThe '''pilotbird''' (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'') is a species of passerine [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[monotypic]] within the genus '''''Pycnoptilus'''''.  The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to south-eastern [[Australia]]. \n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was first described by English ornithologist, [[John Gould]], in 1851. The generic name ''Pycnoptilus'' derives from the Ancient Greek ''pyknos'' 'thick' and ''ptilon'' 'feather'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-20}}</ref> Its specific epithet ''floccosus'' is Late Latin for 'flocked with wool'.<ref name=Helm></ref> There are two subspecies: the nominate subspecies ''Pycnoptilus floccosus floccosus'' lives in alpine areas of New South Wales, such as the [[Snowy Mountains]]; and ''P. f. sandfordi'' lives in lowland forest from the [[Blue Mountains]] to the [[Dandenong Ranges]], near Melbourne.<ref name=Gregory>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Pilotbird (Pycnoptilus floccosus), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.pilotb1.01</ref><ref>Slater, Peter (1974) ''A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines''. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe pilotbird is a large, plump species of acanthizid, measuring around {{convert|18|cm|in}} in length and weighing {{convert|27|g|oz}}. It has a large head and a short bill. The [[plumage]] is mostly brown with scalloping on the chest and an orangish throat.  \n\n==Distribution and Habitat==\nThe pilotbird is found in southeastern New South Wales and eastern Victoria. Its natural [[habitat]] is temperate wet sclerophyll [[forest]]s and occasionally temperate rainforest. \n\n==Behaviour==\nIts name comes from its supposed habit of following [[lyrebird]]s, taking prey that they flush, and also from its call guiding bushmen seeking for lyrebirds.<ref name=Morcombe>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> This habit is well known but seldom observed. The pilotbird is highly terrestrial, feeding on or near the ground and when disturbed it runs swiftly on strong legs.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its call has been described as \"piercing and sweet\".<ref name=Pizzey>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) ''A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref> The male makes a far-carrying call of ''wit-wit-weet-WHEER'' to which the female may respond with a softer ''wit-a-wit-ee''.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref><ref name=Gregory></ref> \n\n===Breeding===\nThe breeding season for the pilotbird is from August to December.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> The globular nest is built with a side-entrance and hidden amongst the accumulated debris on the forest floor.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> It is an untidy construction of bark, ferns, dead leaves and rootlets.<ref name=Pizzey></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1585682}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1851]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Pilotbird\n| image = Pilotbird - Blue Mountains.jpg\n| image_caption = Pilotbird, Blue Mountains\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704513/0 |title=''Pycnoptilus floccosus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Pycnoptilus\n| parent_authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n| species = floccosus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n}}\n\nThe '''pilotbird''' (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'') is a species of passerine [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[monotypic]] within the genus '''''Pycnoptilus'''''.  The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to south-eastern [[Australia]]. \n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was first described by English ornithologist, [[John Gould]], in 1851. The generic name ''Pycnoptilus'' derives from the Ancient Greek ''pyknos'' 'thick' and ''ptilon'' 'feather'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-20}}</ref> Its specific epithet ''floccosus'' is Late Latin for 'flocked with wool'.<ref name=Helm></ref> There are two subspecies: the nominate subspecies ''Pycnoptilus floccosus floccosus'' lives in alpine areas of New South Wales, such as the [[Snowy Mountains]]; and ''P. f. sandfordi'' lives in lowland forest from [[Newcastle, Australia|Newcastle]] to the [[Dandenong Ranges]], near Melbourne.<ref name=Gregory>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Pilotbird (Pycnoptilus floccosus), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.pilotb1.01</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe pilotbird is a large, plump species of acanthizid, measuring around {{convert|18|cm|in}} in length and weighing {{convert|27|g|oz}}. It has a large head and a short bill. The [[plumage]] is mostly brown with scalloping on the chest and an orangish throat.  \n\n==Distribution and Habitat==\nThe pilotbird is found in southeastern New South Wales and eastern Victoria. Its natural [[habitat]] is temperate wet sclerophyll [[forest]]s and occasionally temperate rainforest. \n\n==Behaviour==\nIts name comes from its supposed habit of following [[lyrebird]]s, taking prey that they flush, and also from its call guiding bushmen seeking for lyrebirds.<ref name=Morcombe>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> This habit is well known but seldom observed. The pilotbird is highly terrestrial, feeding on or near the ground and when disturbed it runs swiftly on strong legs.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its call has been described as \"piercing and sweet\".<ref name=Pizzey>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) ''A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref> The male makes a far-carrying call of ''wit-wit-weet-WHEER'' to which the female may respond with a softer ''wit-a-wit-ee''.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref><ref name=Gregory></ref> \n\n===Breeding===\nThe breeding season for the pilotbird is from August to December.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> The globular nest is built with a side-entrance and hidden amongst the accumulated debris on the forest floor.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> It is an untidy construction of bark, ferns, dead leaves and rootlets.<ref name=Pizzey></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1585682}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1851]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pilotbird"}
{"title_page": "Badi Uzzaman", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=September 2015}}\n'''Mohammed Badi Uzzaman Azmi'''<ref name=guardian>{{cite news | first=Tania | last=Ahsan | title=Badi Uzzaman obituary, actor best known for his part in Potter's The Singing Detective | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/jun/21/badi-uzzaman-obituary | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=21 June 2011 | accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref> (8 March 1939 \u2013 14 June 2011), better known as '''Badi Uzzaman''', was a [[Pakistan]]i-[[United Kingdom|British]] television and film actor. According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', Uzzaman was perhaps best known for his role as a hospital patient in the 1986 [[television series]], ''[[The Singing Detective]]'', opposite actor [[Michael Gambon]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl>{{cite news | title=Islamabad: Actor best known for his part in Potter's 'The Singing Detective' | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/jun/21/badi-uzzaman-obituary | work=[[The News International]] | date=27 June 2011}}</ref>  He later appeared in numerous television roles during his career, often as a supporting character, including ''[[Torchwood]]'', ''[[Inspector Morse (TV series)|Inspector Morse]]'', ''[[Coronation Street]]'', ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'', ''[[The Bill]]'' and ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\nUzzaman was born on 8 March 1939, in [[Phulpur, Azamgarh]], [[British India]].<ref name=guardian/> His father worked for the railway industry, so he moved to the city of [[Abbottabad]] in present-day [[Pakistan]].<ref name=guardian/> He continued to move with his family depending on his father's job transfers, which included time in both [[Quetta]] and [[Lahore]].<ref name=guardian/> Uzzaman graduated from Government College, Abbottabad, in 1959, where he studied [[English language|English]] and [[Urdu]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\nUzzaman began his career as a [[radio presenter]] in Pakistan. He switched to acting, appearing in roles of [[Pakistan Television Corporation]] (PTV) following the state-owned channel's launch in 1964.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nIn 1984, Uzzaman was cast in ''Malia'', a Pakistani film about a traveling [[fair]] with a strong, underlying theme against the martial law imposed by the government of General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/> In the film, Uzzaman played five different characters.<ref name=donnell>{{cite book|last=Donnell|first=Alison|title=Companion to contemporary Black British culture|year=2002|publisher=Taylor and Francis|pages=427|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mx53zZLVM_8C}}</ref>  The film was sharply rebuked by Zia's government,<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/> and had to be completed in London.<ref name = donnell/> Uzzaman left Pakistan and was granted [[political asylum]] in the [[United Kingdom]] soon after ''Malia's'' release.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/> He became a [[British citizen]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\nHe is also notable for playing two television characters who were subjected to racially motivated attacks. The first was in the 1989 ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' episode \"Victim of Circumstances\", where he appeared as Bharat Patel, a shopkeeper who was beaten up by two skinheads who had attacked his son in an earlier assault. In 1994, he appeared in the ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'' episode \"To Be a Somebody (Part One)\", in which he played the role of Shahid Ali, a shopkeeper who was the first victim of spree killer Albie Kinsella, played by [[Robert Carlyle]].\n\nAt the age of 72, Uzzaman died of a lung infection on 14 June 2011.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n*''Intekhab'' (1978)\n*''Mehman'' (1978)\n*''[[My Beautiful Laundrette]]'' (1985) - Dealer\n*''Christmas Present'' (1985) - Mr. Amir Mehrban\n*''[[Personal Services]]'' (1987) - Mr. Patel\n*''[[Sammy and Rosie Get Laid]]'' (1987) - Ghost\n*''[[Cry Freedom]]'' (1987) - Mortician's assistant\n*''Bellman and True'' (1987) - Shopkeeper\n*''Karachi'' (1989) - Family father\n*''[[Lebewohl, Fremde]]'' (1991) - Badi\n*''[[K2 (film)|K2]]'' (1991) - Ibrahim\n*''[[Immaculate Conception (film)|Immaculate Conception]]'' (1992) - Dadaji's Retainer\n*''[[Son of the Pink Panther]]'' (1993) - Wasim\n*''[[Bhaji on the Beach]]'' (1993) - Uncle\n*''Brothers in Trouble'' (1995) - Old Ram\n*''[[My Son the Fanatic (film)|My Son the Fanatic]]'' (1997) - Man in mosque\n*''[[You're Dead (film)|You're Dead]]'' (1999) - Dr. Chandra\n*''Mad Cows'' (1999) - Indian shopkeeper\n*''Kevin & Perry Go Large'' (2000) - Shopkeeper\n*''[[The Fourth Angel]]'' (2001) - Dr. Mackay\n*''[[All or Nothing (film)|All or Nothing]]'' (2002) - Passenger #1\n*''Cross My Heart'' (2003) - Vikram\n*''The Baby Juice Express'' (2004) - Singh\n*''[[Yasmin (2004 film)|Yasmin]]'' (2004) - Hassan\n*''[[Red Mercury (film)|Red Mercury]]'' (2005) - Mr. Mulley\n*''[[Eastern Promises]]'' (2007) - Chemist\n*''In Your Dreams'' (2008) - Kung fu waiter\n*''Caught in the Act'' (2008) - Mr. Patel\n*''[[Another Year (film)|Another Year]]'' (2010) - Mr. Gupta\n*''[[Forget Me Not (2010 British film)|Forget Me Not]]'' (2010) - Shopkeeper\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0882732|name=Badi Uzzaman}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uzzaman, Badi}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male television actors]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:English people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pakistani emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Abbottabad]]\n[[Category:British film actors of Pakistani descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=September 2015}}\n'''Mohammed Badi Uzzaman Azmi'''<ref name=guardian>{{cite news | first=Tania | last=Ahsan | title=Badi Uzzaman obituary, actor best known for his part in Potter's The Singing Detective | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/jun/21/badi-uzzaman-obituary | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=21 June 2011 | accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref> (8 March 1939 \u2013 14 June 2011), better known as '''Badi Uzzaman''', was a [[Pakistan]]i-[[United Kingdom|British]] television and film actor. According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', Uzzaman was perhaps best known for his role as a hospital patient in the 1986 [[television series]], ''[[The Singing Detective]]'', opposite actor [[Michael Gambon]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl>{{cite news | title=Islamabad: Actor best known for his part in Potter's 'The Singing Detective' | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/jun/21/badi-uzzaman-obituary | work=[[The News International]] | date=27 June 2011}}</ref>  He later appeared in numerous television roles during his career, often as a supporting character, including ''[[Torchwood]]'', ''[[Inspector Morse (TV series)|Inspector Morse]]'', ''[[Coronation Street]]'', ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'', ''[[The Bill]]'' and ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\nUzzaman was born on 8 March 1939, in [[Phulpur, Azamgarh]], [[British India]].<ref name=guardian/> His father worked for the railway industry, so he moved to the city of [[Abbottabad]] in present-day [[Pakistan]].<ref name=guardian/> He continued to move with his family depending on his father's job transfers, which included time in both [[Quetta]] and [[Lahore]].<ref name=guardian/> Uzzaman graduated from Government College, Abbottabad, in 1959, where he studied [[English language|English]] and [[Urdu]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\nUzzaman began his career as a [[radio presenter]] in Pakistan. He switched to acting, appearing in roles of [[Pakistan Television Corporation]] (PTV) following the state-owned channel's launch in 1964.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nIn 1984, Uzzaman was cast in ''Malia'', a Pakistani film about a traveling [[fair]] with a strong, underlying theme against the martial law imposed by the government of General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/> In the film, Uzzaman played five different characters.<ref name=donnell>{{cite book|last=Donnell|first=Alison|title=Companion to contemporary Black British culture|year=2002|publisher=Taylor and Francis|pages=427|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mx53zZLVM_8C}}</ref>  The film was sharply rebuked by Zia's government,<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/> and had to be completed in London.<ref name = donnell/> Uzzaman left Pakistan and was granted [[political asylum]] in the [[United Kingdom]] soon after ''Malia's'' release.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/> He became a [[British citizen]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\nHe is also notable for playing two television characters who were subjected to racially motivated attacks. The first was in the 1989 ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' episode \"Victim of Circumstances\", where he appeared as Bharat Patel, a shopkeeper who was beaten up by two skinheads who had attacked his son in an earlier assault. In 1994, he appeared in the ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'' episode \"To Be a Somebody (Part One)\", in which he played the role of Shahid Ali, a shopkeeper who was the first victim of spree killer Albie Kinsella, played by [[Robert Carlyle]].\n\nAt the age of 72, Uzzaman died of a lung infection on 14 June 2011.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=newsintl/>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n*''Intekhab'' (1978)\n*''Mehman'' (1978)\n*''[[My Beautiful Laundrette]]'' (1985) - Dealer\n*''Christmas Present'' (1985) - Mr. Amir Mehrban\n*''[[Personal Services]]'' (1987) - Mr. Patel\n*''[[Sammy and Rosie Get Laid]]'' (1987) - Ghost\n*''[[Cry Freedom]]'' (1987) - Mortician's assistan